<subSubSection box="[151,1108,1633,1658]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1633,2021]" box="[151,1108,1633,1658]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1633,1658]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Forewing length: males 10.5–11.0 mm (n = 10), females 12.1 mm (n = 3).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="172" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1633,2021]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Freitas" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Stichel" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[199,382,1670,1693]" class="Insecta" family="Riodinidae" genus="Sertania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guttata" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[199,382,1670,1693]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Sertania guttata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[390,520,1669,1694]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[390,520,1669,1694]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
appears at first glance as a small 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1851" box="[908,1000,1670,1693]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Aricoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[908,1000,1670,1693]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Aricoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with white spots much like sympatric 
<taxonomicName authority="(Stichel, 1910)" authorityName="Stichel" authorityYear="1910" baseAuthorityName="Stichel" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[151,511,1705,1730]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Aricoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="signata">
<emphasis box="[151,334,1706,1729]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Aricoris signata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Stichel" box="[349,503,1705,1730]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" refString="Stichel, H. F. E. J. (1910) Vorarbeiten zu einer Revision der Riodinidae Grote (Erycinidae Swains.) (Lep. Rhop.). Berliner entomologische Zeitschrift, 55, 9 - 103." type="journal article" year="1910">Stichel, 1910</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but can be easily distinguished by the scalloped distal margin of the FW and the lacking of the spot at the base of the HW cell Sc + R1. Differences with the additional species in the genus are discussed in following sections.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="172" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1633,2021]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1816,1841]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Variation.</emphasis>
This species shows some variation between and within populations regarding the extent of yelloworange scaling on both wings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="173" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1633,2021]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,536]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="173" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,497,1888,1913]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Biology and distribution.</emphasis>
The type locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Freitas" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Stichel" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[730,911,1888,1912]" class="Insecta" family="Riodinidae" genus="Sertania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guttata" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[730,911,1888,1912]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Sertania guttata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[918,1047,1888,1913]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[918,1047,1888,1913]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
in Mendoza and some distribution records in La Rioja (Argentina) correspond to xeric habitats, known as Monte vegetation (
<figureCitation box="[1166,1250,1924,1949]" captionStart="FIGURES 34 – 37" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1200,1222]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,194,1179]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,193,1179]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 34 – 37. Overview of Sertania gen. nov. habitats in South American ‘ dry diagonal’. 34 – 35, Sertania guttata comb. nov., monte vegetation (34) in Anillaco, La Rioja, and Chaco serrano (35) in Capilla del Monte, Cordoba, Argentina; 36, Sertania jaibensis comb. nov., stat. nov., rocky montane fields in Sempre Vivas National Park, Buenópolis, Minas Gerais, Brazil; 37, Sertania lambedor comb. nov., stat. nov., arboreal caatinga in Custódia, Pernambuco, Brazil. Photos (36) by CA Iserhard and (37) by DHA Melo." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/892889/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
), part of a warm shrub desert at the east of the Andean mountains (
<bibRefCitation author="Giacomelli" box="[705,895,1960,1985]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" refString="Giacomelli, E. (1911) Lepidopteros riojanos nuevos o poco conocidos. Anales de la Sociedad Cientifica Argentina, 72 (1), 19 - 40." type="journal article" year="1911">Giacomelli 1911</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Roig-Junent" box="[906,1171,1960,1985]" pageId="7" pageNumber="172" refString="Roig-Junent, S., Flores, G., Claver, S., Debandi, G. &amp; Marvaldi, A. (2001) Monte Desert (Argentina): insect biodiversity and natural areas. Journal of Arid Environments, 47, 77 - 94. https: // doi. org / 10.1006 / jare. 2000.0688" type="journal article" year="2001">
Roig-Juñent 
<emphasis box="[1049,1098,1960,1984]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">et al</emphasis>
. 2001
</bibRefCitation>
). Most of the additional records are from Chaco vegetation formations in lowlands and mountain areas of “chaco serrano” (
<figureCitation box="[1292,1378,1996,2021]" captionStart="FIGURES 34 – 37" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1200,1222]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,194,1179]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1435,193,1179]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 34 – 37. Overview of Sertania gen. nov. habitats in South American ‘ dry diagonal’. 34 – 35, Sertania guttata comb. nov., monte vegetation (34) in Anillaco, La Rioja, and Chaco serrano (35) in Capilla del Monte, Cordoba, Argentina; 36, Sertania jaibensis comb. nov., stat. nov., rocky montane fields in Sempre Vivas National Park, Buenópolis, Minas Gerais, Brazil; 37, Sertania lambedor comb. nov., stat. nov., arboreal caatinga in Custódia, Pernambuco, Brazil. Photos (36) by CA Iserhard and (37) by DHA Melo." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/892889/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="172">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
), but never above 
<quantity box="[298,388,151,176]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="173" unit="m" value="1500.0">1500 m</quantity>
. Adult habits are sedentary and males were observed perching for long periods with closed wings on low bushes or on the ground. In consecutive visits, different males are found in the same places in an apparent territorial behavior (
<figureCitation box="[480,611,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 44" captionStartId="12.[151,264,957,979]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,936]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[152,1435,193,936]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 44. Live adults of Sertania gen. nov. in the field. 39 – 41, Sertania guttata comb. nov., male in Capilla del Monte (39 – 40) and female (41) in Carlos Paz, Cordoba, Argentina; 42 – 44, Sertania lambedor comb. nov., stat. nov., perching male in Custódia (42) and Floresta (43) and female (44) on flower in Salgueiro, Pernambuco, Brazil. Scale bar = 1 cm. Photos (41) by G. Muriziasco and (42 – 44) by DHA Melo." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/892893/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="173">Figs 39–40</figureCitation>
). Females were encountered nectaring on flowers with wings spread. The range of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Freitas" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Stichel" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[255,364,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Riodinidae" genus="Sertania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guttata" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[255,364,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="173">S. guttata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[374,505,260,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[374,505,260,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="173">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
includes central and western Argentina in the Provinces of Catamarca, Cordoba, Formosa, La Rioja, Mendoza, Salta and Santiago del Estero (
<bibRefCitation author="Volkmann" box="[851,1234,295,320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="173" refString="Volkmann, L. &amp; Nunez-Bustos, E. (2010) Mariposas Serranas de Argentina Central. Tomo 1: Papilionidae, Pieridae, Lycaenidae, Riodinidae. Equipo Grafico, Huerta Grande, Argentina, 140 pp." type="book" year="2010">Volkmann &amp; Nuñez-Bustos 2010</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nunez-Bustos" pageId="8" pageNumber="173" refString="Nunez-Bustos, E. &amp; Volkmann, L. (2013) Lepidopterofauna de mariposas diurnas de las Sierras de Guasayan, Provincia de Santiago del Estero, Argentina (Lepidoptera: Papilionoidea y Hesperioidea). SHILAP Revista de Lepidopterologia, 41, 383 - 393." type="journal article" year="2013">Nuñez-Bustos &amp; Volkmann 2013</bibRefCitation>
). In western Paraguay, it is recorded in Chaco areas (
<bibRefCitation author="Drechsel" box="[932,1099,332,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="173" refString="Drechsel, U. (2016) Paraguay Biodiversidad. Available from: http: // www. pybio. org / (accessed 7 March 2017)" type="journal article" year="2016">Drechsel 2016</bibRefCitation>
) and although it should occur in similar habitats in Bolivia (
<bibRefCitation author="Jauffret" box="[484,699,367,392]" pageId="8" pageNumber="173" refString="Jauffret, P., Jauffret, J. C. &amp; Pessoa, A. (2008) Etudes preliminaires sur la faune des Riodinidae du nord-est bresilien - Etat du Ceara. (Lepidoptera). Description d'une espece et de trois sous especes nouvelles (9 eme note). Lambillionea, CVIII (4), 501 - 510." type="journal article" year="2008">
Jauffret 
<emphasis box="[578,634,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="173">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
) its presence there has yet to be confirmed.
</paragraph>
